On September 19, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1993 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately fifty (50) gallons of product to the trailer floor and parking lot. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Alpha-Omega Training and Compliance (AOTC) to remediate the impacted site. AOTC transferred the damaged drum from the trailer to an 85-gallon overpack for transport and disposal. The crew deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer and concrete pavement. AOTC utilized hand tools to collect the spent absorbents into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. AOTC staged the drums onsite to be processed via R+Ls normal waste stream.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

On September 19, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1161 was crushed during transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site.  HCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the UN1161-impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents and the damaged pail were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum to be staged onsite disposal by R+L.

column168: The driver of the truck was traveling on highway #110 at Km 30.5 jurisdiction of Bo. Avocado from the municipality of Aguadilla. It was transporting 11,000.00 gallons of Jet Fuel, soon to reach its destination the truck crashed, overturning the truck and tank, causing a spill, an estimated jet fuel loss of 1,540 gallons on the ground.  state agencies were activated for emergency management; Environmental Quality Board, Puerto Rico Police, Firefighters, Transportation Bureau and Other public services and Environmental Emergency cleaning company to clean the area impacted by the spill.  Industrial cranes were required to lift the tank and truck. The product left the truck through the blind cover on the tank due to the pressure that the product exerted on it.  The estimated time to complete the work of moving the truck and tank from the accident site was 6 hours.  The immediate activation of the resources that manage emergencies and the actions of the personnel who work with the management of the containment and cleaning of the hazardous material, ensured that the impact was controlled.
column169: The drivers were made aware of the importance of resting outside of their working hours. It is understood that the driver did not monitor his sleeping hours while he was on his personal hours. column168: On 09/13/2023 at approximately 1815, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 4553408 at the station location in Portland, reporting an undeclared corrosive spill.  Spillage was detected from two separate shipments, each consisting of two plastic bottles, packageed sideways, in one fiberboard box.  Due to an insecure closure, one jug from each box leaked, resulting a spillage.  Per an online safety data sheet, these shipments are classified as UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide Solution.  Neither package adorned were marked or labeled as dangerous goods, nor did either package have the required paperwork and appropriate packaging, in accordance with IATA regulations.  Both shipments are being held, pending an FAA investigation.

column168: An FRA inspector observed liquid on the side of tank car # GATX 80428 appearing to be leaking from the manway cover (approximately 1/2 way down the side of the car) while performing a regulatory compliance check at the CN Glenn Yard in Chicago, IL. The inspector notified the CN Dangerous Goods Officer who responded to the incident location. The CN Dangerous Goods Officer's inspection of tank car revealed liquid leaking from the gasket sealing surface between the manway nozzle and the manway cover plate indicating a possible gasket failure. The liquid on the side of the tank car previously noted by the FRA inspector was nearing the bottom side of the tank car when the CN DGO arrived. The nitrogen pad pressure was relieved from the tank car. The manway cover was then opened for gasket inspection purposes. The (6) manway cover swing bolt nuts required a 36" pipe wrench and lubricating oil on the bolt threads to be loosened indicating the cover has not been opened for an extended period of time. The 20" manway cover lid gasket was removed and inspected. The inspection revealed the gasket to be delaminated in several areas and showed signs of deterioration throughout. The lid gasket was replaced with a 20" Teflon rim nozzle gasket and re-secured by the CN DGO. A response contractor decontaminated the tank car exterior and re-applied a nitrogen pad to the interior. The shipper listed on the waybill was notified of the incident through a Chemtrec report. The car will be released for continued transportation pending an OTMA 3 for an un-related defect.

XPO Logistics terminal XSA experienced a UN1760 Clothesline Fresh BLD 2 release from a 5-gallon poly pail and a Non-Regulated Xcelente release from a 2-liter poly jug. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed all 5-gallons of the UN1760 Clothesline Fresh BLD 2 released as all as all 2-liters of the Xcelente released together. The products impacted a 12’ x 4’ area of the trailer floor and a 12’ x 4’ area of the concrete lot below due to forklift punctures. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged empty jugs and spend absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: PVS Transportation driver was unloading the product into the customer's tank while a customer's  employee was monitoring the gauge on the tank(because the gauge was not visible from the truck).  The customer's employee switched the valve to unload into a different tank when the first tank was  full and another employee switched the valve back causing 150 gallons to overflow from the tank  into containment. The overflow lasted approximately 45 seconds.
column169: PVS Safety Team met with our customer on communication between employees and the importance of one  person being held responsible for the unloading of product and monitoring the valves between tanks.  The customer took 100% responsibility for the communication breakdown between the two separate  employees and will assign one employee to unload from start to finish to prevent recurrence.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: On September 19, 2023, at 0420 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by MC Tank Transport Inc personnel in Mobile, Alabama regarding the release of approximately (30) gallon of Farmin DM2470 (Amines, liquid, corrosive, n.o.s. (Alkyl (C12-C14 Dimethylamine) UN2735 8, II) from a tanker.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release.  Upon arrival, contractors confirmed that the release was caused by loose flange bolts on the tanker and was contained to a 50' x 2' area of asphalt, and a 1' x 1' area of nearby soil. Contractors were able to clean up the release with absorbents, pad, and the proper PPE. They used hand tools to scrap the affected soil, and tightened the flange bolts, so the cargo could be forwarded on to the original consignee.  All waste generated was containerized in (2) 55-gallon poly drums which was then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal. No further remediation of this site is warranted.

column168: on 09/12/2023 at approximately 1845, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 234302 at the hub facility in Newark, reporting an undeclared flammable liquid spill.  The shipment is a gas-powered generator, containing a resudue of gasoline.  The shipment was discovered due to odor and a stained outer package.  The shipment was not prepared as a fully regulated dangerous goods shipment, without having the required marking, labeling, packaging and paperwork, in accordance with IATA regulations.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Kropp Environmental Contractors (KEC) to remediate the impacted site. Crews collected the damaged 55-gallon drum and placed in in a 95-gallon over pack drum for disposal. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and worked them in with hand tools. All hydrogen peroxide impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 95-gallon drum and added to R+L's waste stream for disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal LSX experienced a UN1903 MBC 516 release from a 275-gallon poly. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-cups of material released to a 5’ x 5’ area of the trailer floor due to the lid of the tote being crushed in as a result of improper loading. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. The old tote was cut up and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. Soda ash was then deployed along with absorbents to clean the impacted area. All impacted waste was placed into a 5-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Technically this spill was related to our driver fueling the tractor trailer fuel tank and not the actual trailer vessel. However, Driver bypassed safety feature on the fuel dispenser handle by putting something under it to hold it open. Came into the terminal while fueling and when he returned fuel had spilled from his tank into the gravel and traveled downhill to the tree line. CDG managed the spill cleanup. Estimated gallons of diesel fuel was 30 gallons. Again, this is from fueling the tractor and not related to the trailer vessel.

When opening the box for further inspection, one of the glass liters was broken and lost all of the content that was inside, the other 3 glass liters had no damage. I grabbed the broken glass pieces with my gloves and threw them away after I took pictures for the report. Then obtained a large yellow barrel and put a blue hazmat bag inside to place the undamaged products in and placed in the hazmat cage until further instructions are given. DescribePack: This package was improperly handled which led to one of the glass liters breaking and losing all the content that was inside. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: By the time I was inspecting the hazmat the liquid had already dried up but in case of further leakage that went unnoticed I placed a cardboard box underneath the original hazmat box.

On September 12, 2023, one (1) 275-gallon tote of UN1792 had a faulty valve and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site.  HCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted dock and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 15-gallon drum. Crews transferred the material from the 330-gallon tote into a new one. HCE personnel cut up the old tote and placed the pieces into three (3) 55-gallon drums. All containers were staged onsite for future disposal.

column168: On September 15, 2023, CN transportation crews observed UTLX 130231 (Residue Last Contained / UN 1789 / Hydrochloric Acid / Class 8) venting from the top during a roll-by inspection inbound into Geismar yard.  The railcar was isolated, all required notifications made.  CN Contractor responded.  Upon approaching the railcar, vapors were observed coming from the top.  Upon closer inspection, puddled liquid was observed on the pressure plate.  The fill hole cover bolts were checked and could be easily turned by a gloved hand.  The puddled liquid was tested with ph paper and showed acidic. The fill hole cover bolts were tightened, and the leak was secured.  The puddled liquid was neutralized, and the exterior of the railcar was decontaminated.  The railcar was released back into transportation and allowed to continue onto destination.

column168: On 09/13/2023, at 0239 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard discovered OLNX 32004, a residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and West Virginia DEP were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2023-0913-00015). Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the fill hole cover closed however gasketing material was displaced and preventing a proper seal resulting in a vapor release of lading. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Rob Cline of Tetra Technologies, phone 304-482-7655. Contractor personnel properly installed the gasket and fill port cover without incident thus securing the release. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 232 NARRI: 90

Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. column168: Driver had loaded diesel into compartments 1,3 and 4, Driver states he put out cones and stuck tanks. Driver started unloading Compartment 4 into tank 5 and Compartment 1 into tank 4.  Driver states that tank 5 had 81” in tank prior to dropping and tank 4 had 80”.  Compartment 4 Tank 5 drop completed, and the driver drained the hose and disconnected from truck but left the drop hooked up to ground connection.  Driver was planning to move the hose and drop gun from compartment 4 tank 5 to compartment 3 tank 7.  Driver checked the other hose and notice the well on tank 4 started to fill up.  Driver shut down unloading from compartment 1.  The manifold system between the tanks caused tank 5 to fill the well along with product to come back out of hose on the ground.  Driver tried to cap the end of the hose that was still hooked up to tank 5 drop and was sprayed with diesel.  Driver had to drop the rest of compartment 1 into tank 7.  All the diesel tanks are Mani folded together.
column169: Tank issues were reported to the Customer.  Driver was coached on proper hose movement and capping end of open hoses.

When driver went to go hook to trailer in drop lot he noticed liquid coming from trailer on the gravel lot. Driver then notified facility manager and a team was dispatcher out to facilitate the clean up. The trailer was moved to the dock to pull the container off and put on a containment pallet and absorbent was put down to prevent any spread of the material until the team could start the clean up. The response team arrived and had to remove the material from the container and put into a new one. Gravel from the lot had to be removed creating three 55 gallon drums of material. The inner liner of the bag was determined to be damaged from when it was filled causing the release. From the time it was identified to when clean up was complete was approximately 4 hours.
column169: Training was redon on how the material is to be put into the container paying special attention to maintaining the integrity of the liner.

column168: A CN Mechanical employee observed liquid dripping from the bottom outlet valve cap of tank car # CTCX 731039 while perform rail car inspections on an inbound train at the CN Waterloo Yard in Waterloo, IA. The employee notified the on duty transportation manager who in turn made all internal notifications to initiate a response to the incident. A CN Dangerous Goods Officer performed an inspection of the tank car and found the bottom outlet valve to be leaking from the threads of the bottom outlet valve cap as a result of the BOV not creating a proper seal and the BOV cap not tight enough to contain the leak. (The BOV cap was found to be tool tight and the BOV valve in the fully closed position upon initial inspection). The BOV valve handle was cycled several times to the open and closed position to free any debris that may have been trapped in the BOV sealing surface potentially causing the leak. The leak persisted after cycling the valve. A 24" pipe wrench was then used to turn the BOV operating stem in a counter clockwise direction in an attempt to further close the valve. The leak persisted after using the pipe wrench. A 36" pipe wrench was used to further tighten the BOV cap to stop the leak. Tightening the BOV cap further stopped the leak. (Approximately 1/4 turn). The BOV cap was loosened but not fully removed to observe the leakage volume during the above attempts to fully seat the valve. The tank car will be transloaded, cleaned and purged prior to being released for transportation. 09-20-2023 The tank car was transloaded into a shipper provided empty tank car. It was then cleaned and purged of all hazardous material. The BOV cap was removed so the gasket could be inspected. The gasket was found to be severely damaged and cut which ultimately contributed to the leak.
Associate did not block and/or brace freight properly for transport.  Freight was crushed causing release of product.

column168: On 9/9/2023 at approximately 1430, Dangerous Good Administration received a call from Employee 658069 at the hub facility in Memphis, reporting a spill incident, involving an undeclared corrosive liquid. The shipment consists of 1 fiberboard box conaining six 64oz bottles of Clobber drain cleaner.  Per an online safety data safety, the shipment contained concentrated sulfuric acid and is classifed as UN 1830.  Three of the bottles spilled from the package resulting in sizable spill and contaminating an estimated 30 packages.  A vendor was called in the contain the spill.  The affected shipments have been handles accrodingly.   Further investigation revealed the spilled package was not declared as dangerous goods, in compliance with IATA Regulations.  The shipment is places in a salvage drum and is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.

XPO Logistics terminal XCN experienced a UN3272 Disperbyk-161 release from a 55-gallon steel drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 53-gallons of material released to a 58’ x 10’ area of the concrete lot below the dock and a 15’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas and then collected into (3) 55-gallon metal drums. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly overpack. The impacted trailer, concrete lot, and trench drain that flows to the onsite OWS were all pressure washed. All impacted water and skimmed material from the trench drain were collected and containerized into an additional 55-gallon metal drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On September 24, 2023 at 20:37 Transportation personnel in the Conrail Livernois Terminal reported that ,GATX 2013  a loaded tank car of FLUOROSILICIC ACID leaking from top of the tank car upon movement. Additionally,  during routine switching operations a Conrail Conductor was splashed with acid from the improperly secured tank car. The Conductor was immediately brought in to remove affected clothing and shower of any impacted skin. No reportable injury was encountered as the Conductors and Terminal Supervisions actions removed all material before any health effects took place. The car was isolated and the shipper/consignee PVS was notified directly via phone. Enviroserve, an approved Conrail Contractor was notified to respond, inspect and secure the tank car. Enviroserve personnel, investigated the leak and found the source of the leak to be from the rupture disk assembly. Upon further inspection it was found that the inspection cap was hanging off the housing and no rupture disk was in place beneath the assembly. Additionally, there was no required surge protection on the rupture disk assembly. Enviroserve placed the appropriate rupture disk and resecured the assembly. The tank car was then held until the proper surge protection device could be placed in the assembly. Conrail and Enviroserve worked with the car owner and Steve Kuz, Alltrantec 519-718-8377 to secure the proper service equipment.  On October 4, 2023 the new surge protection device was installed on the tank car and it was released back into transportation.    Cause Code: 437 5 x ( 5 + 5 + 0 ) x ( 2+ 2 ) =  200

On September 1, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1789 was crushed during transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the impacted site. EWI personnel deployed neutralizing, granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and swept them in with hand tools. All freight was wiped down and repalletized for further handling by R+L terminal personnel. All spent absorbents, cleanup debris, and the empty, damaged 5-gallon pail were collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drum that was labeled and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: Driver got lost, drove onto a narrow rural road and could not negotiate a sharp tum causing left rear of trailer to leave road and rolled down an embankment. When the trailer overturned, it hit a small tree which had branches that entered the spill dam/ rollover protection area and hit the 3/4 inch air inlet line at the base of the Fort Valve PRD and broke the 3/4 inch stainless steel nipple for the air inlet line. There were no other package failures. At this point the cargo tank lost approximately 300 gallons, ER personnel would not allow us to stop the leak until there the tank was anchored by a recovery unit. We requested a tow truck to anchor it around 5:30 on Wed 9-13-2023, but one was never called. At approximately 7:00 PM, the incident commander decided to put off all efforts on hold until 7:30/8:00 AM the following morning due to location and darkness setting in. Due to no cell phone coverage in the area, we had requested ER personnel made all required ^ notifications to EPA, CaIOES, NRC, etc. California Highway Patrol was IC, Alameda Fire was on site, Ambulance, Fish and Wildlife, local environmental agency, the Sf Water district, etc were all onsite. At 07:30 on 9-14-23, a recovery 65 ton rotator arrived on site to secure the trailer. At approximately 8:30 we were allowed to do damage assessment on the trailer and found the source of the leak, drove a redwood plug onto it and stopped the leak. We then hooked up a 2 inch hose between the discharge line and a 70 barrel vacuum tank. By this time, since plugging was delayed, the cargo tank lost approximately 2,000 gallons of product. Tank was emptied, recovered and uprighted.
column169: Better delivery instructions for these rural deliveries. Better signage for the delivery point and mandate that if the driver gets lost to stop and call dispatch for directions. He was also misdirected by both fire personnel and Pacific Gas and Electric utilies crews when he initially got lost.

During receiving/off-loading at Veolia's facility in Phoenix, AZ Veolia employees observed liquid coming from the bottom a 30 gallon fiber drum that was stacked on top of 55 gallon poly drums. Vials containing liquid COD reagent were packed into a fiber drum with no added absorbent or cushioning material. A 6 mil poly bag containing the vials was used as a liner/inner packaging, but apparently it was not sufficient to stop a release of liquid. The containers were removed from the receiving area and placed into the processing area within facility on a spill containment pallet. Notifications were made to the shipping location with instructions to ship this type of material in poly drums in the future to avoid spillage.
column169: Changes or improved operating procedures include: 1) Review proper shipping techniques frequently with all locations and customers shipping to Veolia and 2) Retrain employees as necessary on proper packaging of vials containing liquids.

column168: On September 18, 2023, at 2013 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in El Paso, Texas regarding the release of approximately 2-gallons of AIRSTONE™ 786H-B WIND INFUSION HARDENER (UN2735, Amines, Liquid, Corrosive, N.O.S, 8, II) from (1) 275-gallon plastic tote. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release was contained to a 1’x 53’ and a 1’ x 1’ area on the trailer floor. There was also a second tote with hardened crystallization on it, but with no leak. Contractors were able to transfer the remaining product from the damaged tote into a new tote, clean the crystallization off the second tote, and the release was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DF, which was then taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

On September 27, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN3098 was dropped by a forklift and released approximately five (5) gallons to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site.  TLE personnel deployed poly sheeting, pH neutralizers, soda ash, granular absorbents, and pad absorbents to theUN3098-impacted areas and collected them with hand tools. TLE personnel cut out the impacted wood debris from the trailer and after collection of waste and debris flushed the trailer. All spent absorbents and debris were collected into two (2) lined 35-gallon poly drums, one with the impacted, diluted pail inside and the other with miscellaneous waste and debris, along with a lined 55-gallon poly drum containing mixed waste and cleanup debris.

column168: Driver did not notice that this was a vapor-recovery tank even though it was diesel fuel.(Customer took out the mid-grade gasoline product and replaced it with diesel product) The driver failed to lock down the down spout fitting onto the pipe fitting. The tank built up presseure as there was a pressure release vent cap in place, and the least resistanse which was the non-coupled fitting, blew off the pipe fitting, releasing(spilling) product onto the ground. The driver was at the rear of the trailer doing paperwork, rather than at the point of delivery. The fuel ran down hill onto the street and entered the city sewer system. All of the product ran down hill thru the city sewer system about a block and was captured at a holding tank prior to entering a lake. No product entered the lake. Booms where placed and then replaced to collect the spilled product.
column169: I have requested the owner of the store to remove the vapor-recovery system from the the tank and replace the check-valve vapor cap with a standard vapor cap. column168: SequenceEvent: Driver gave 2 different accounts of the incident to QA and P&D.  Initially, driver said that it fell out of his truck, but not while he was at a delivery stop or a pickup stop and he couldn't remember where it happened.  He said that someone helped him hose down the liquid when they read that the material was called "Dishmachine Detergent."  The driver gave the empty drum to QA and the inside of his truck was visible with pickups on the floor of the truck at that time.  There were no additional damages from that Work Area.  The following day, P&D was told that the spill occurred inside the delivery truck and that "they had hosed it down", but did not say when or where the spill occurred nor did they say who helped the driver clean up the truck since the Hazmat had been the only damaged package to return to the station.  Only the empty drum was brought back, no cleanup material. DescribePack: Drum is scuffed and covered in sandy dirt.  The lid appears to have come open partially or partially put back on after coming off. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Driver said someone helped him "hose it down", but not who or where or what was done with the cleanup material if any was used.  Empty drum was brought back to the station.

column168: Tank truck and pup trailer were involved in a rollover incident while trying to enter the customer's site- Costco Wholesale, 300 W. Dimond Blvd, Anchorage, AK. The tank shell failed when it experienced an abrasion during the rollover. The driver was removed from the vehicle and the fire dept placed putty on the tank shell to stop the release of additional hazardous material. Once the scene was rendered safe by the fire department, cleanup operations commenced with the placement of absorbent boom and absorbent materials. Storm drains and manways were blocked. Released matter was contained to less than a 200 square foot area. Product was transferred out of the containers and delivered to the intended destination. Variance of what was lifted versus metered into the customer tank was approximately 20USWG.

XPO Logistics terminal XIN experienced a UN1760 GF PHOS 417 release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 150-gallons of material released to two areas of the concrete dock floor each measuring 20’ x 20’. The release was caused due to a forklift puncture. The remaining material in the tote was transferred into a new tote. Water was deployed to neutralize the impacted areas and absorbents were then used to collect all material. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all cleanup debris into (9) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Enviroserve was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 1ft-by-1ft area of the trailer floor and terminal floor and estimated that one (1) gallon of material was released due to damaged valve assembly causing the release of material. Enviroserve personnel transferred the remaining material in the damaged 330-gallon metal tote to eight 55-gallon metal drums. Enviroserve personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and collected the spent material and placed into one of the 55-gallon metal drums. The generated waste was staged onsite in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

SequenceEvent: Improperly marked pkg made its way to the destination without being entered in the Hazmat Acceptance Process (HAP). The destination station improperly failed the pkg in HAP and improperly attempted to return the pkg to the shipper. Destination station did not use the required DOT-Special Permit nor did they provide the required documentation for an Unprocessed Hazmat pkg being returned. Shipper provided incorrectly filled out Hazmat Certification and OP-900LL Hazmat tags. Number and Type Packaging is not acceptable, Technical Name is the same as the Number and Type Packaging. Pkg has a Ltd Qty diamond printed on it indicating the pkg could have shipped as such rather than fully regulated. Contents leaked wetting and staining the contents and carton. Due to the time and distance the pkg has travelled it is unknown how long the inner containers leaked. DescribePack: Loose caps on 2 x 1.3 L plastic bottles. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Pkg was kept upright. Once in the possession of personnel responsible for Hazmat damages/compliance, HAP the pkg was placed in a lined Hazmat salvage pail to await disposition after reporting.

On 9/23/2023 at 0139 hours a 16 rail car and 1 locomotive derailed in Hyattsville, Maryland at BAA 33.4 milepost at the Baltimore Avenue crossing intersecting Emerson Street.  UTLX910325 (residue UN2370 Hexene) and UTLX91084 (residue UN1075 liquefied petroleum gas) derailed on their side with no leaks.  14 closed hopper cars with polyurethane pellets derailed with various orientations and varying levels of leaked pellets.   The shipper, Shell Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC (report 2023-0923-00020).  HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, as well as (2) Managers of Hazardous Materials from CSX, were dispatched to the scene to assess the damaged hazardous material tank cars, contain leaked pellets, and remediate a minor fuel release from the derailed locomotive.  The crossing at Baltimore Avenue and Emerson Street were closed for approximately 7 days as a result of the derailment.

Diesel fuel was observed leaking from the manway on the VMSX 310119 while at the Balmer railyard on 9/8/23.  The car was isolated for inspection.  Hazmat responders identified the release as coming from the manway sealing area underneath the cover.  Upon inspection it was found that the manway gasket had not been applied resulting in a small release of diesel fuel to the car body.  Crews added a gasket and secured the car.  Release loss estimates are based upon visual observations of the responders.

Spilt liquid was cleaned up with paper towels, and leaked on packages were removed from trailer to be repacked.  No packages that were leaked on were damaged. column168: PPC employee and receiving facility employee were unloading the drums from inside the trailer to a  location outside. The employees tried to use a pallet jack but were unable to get it under the  pallet. The employees proceeded to take one drum at a time from off of the pallet and move them by  dolly. There was no sign or indication that the drum was leaking when the employees were moving the  drums. When the receiving facility employee moved the last drum, the bottom of the drum cracked.  The crack was a total failure (please see attached photo #1) and all fluid was released quickly  inside the trailer.  The fluids ran out of the trailer and onto the asphalt where it gathered along the cement curb.  Employees worked together and set down absorbent boom and pads to contain the waste from spreading  further. Fluids stayed onsite in the immediate area and didn't enter any waterways, public property  or roads. Internal response team from the facility cleaned up the spill. Waste materials were then collected and placed into new drums for disposal.
column169: Drums were not provided by PPC. PPC will utilize a checklist to inspect drums and other containers  more from clients for transport. The PPC driver and a representative for the receiving company will use  the same checklist to verify the conditions of the drums and signs of leaking material inside the  truck before accepting and offloading the load. Based on the photo provided by the receiving  company, the drum appears like it might have been older and/or stored for a while. The dolly in the  photo (see photo 2) is not the correct equipment to transport or maneuver the poly drums.

column168: On September 6, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote containing UN1805 was damaged due to falling off the lift gate and released approximately eighty (80) gallons of product to the soil. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from SET Environmental (SET) to remediate the impacted site. SET personnel deployed poly sheeting around the impacted areas and patched the one (1) damaged tote. The crew returned the next day to perform a tote transfer. SET personnel conducted a gravity transfer of the remaining material from the damaged tote into one (1) new 330-gallon tote provided by on-site management. Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to the impacted area. Once neutralized, SET personnel utilized a back hoe to remove the impacted soil. The excavated area was backfilled with clean soil, graded to match pre-existing topography, and covered with erosion matting to promote vegetative growth. All impacted soil was collected and containerized into one (1) roll off and staged on-site pending waste profiling for disposal purposes. One (1) background and one (1) confirmation sample were obtained from the site, placed into laboratory approved containers, and transported under chain of custody protocol to the laboratory.

column168: At 0815 EDT the captain on inbound flight FFT1167 was taxing into gate 15 at Orlando International  Airport (MCO) and called Ops and stated, "we have a fire". Ops notified the Comm Center and the  airport fire department, which met the aircraft at the gate. We got the approval to pull the bridge  up to the aircraft as it was advised the fire was out. The fire department entered the aircraft and  determined it was safe to deplane the passengers.  A woman, seated in row 7, tote bag began to smoke and catch on fire. The tote bag had a vape pen, a  loose spare battery and a laptop in the tote bag. The flight attendants were quick to respond with  a fire extinguisher and a fire containment bag and were able to put the fire out as fast as  possible by using the fire containment bag to place the tote bag in it to stop the fire. The tote  bag sustained heavy damage. Determined the tote bag contained a vape pen, a loose spare battery,  and a laptop. Unsure if the vape pen or the loose battery began the thermal runaway as both were  heavily damaged. The laptop was in the early stages of melting. There was no damage to the aircraft  nor injured passengers on board. The fire department collected the fire containment bag with the  tote bag in it. The passenger did eventually collect her laptop that was in the bag after speaking  with the fire department and Frontier security.

column168: On September 26, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2735 was punctured and released approximately fifty (50) gallons of product to the trailer floor and concrete parking lot. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to remediate the impacted site.  ES placed the damaged drum into one (1) 85-gallon overpack for transport and disposal. ES deployed a neutralizing agent and absorbents to the trailer floor and concrete parking lot. The crew utilized absorbent pads to wipe underneath the trailer. ES collected the spent absorbents into five (5) drums for transport and disposal. On September 28, 2023, ES returned to the site. ES utilized a combination of a neutralizer, absorbent wipes, and hand tools to remove the residue buildup generated from the original cleanup. The crew placed the spent neutralizer and absorbents into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. ES staged the drum onsite to be processed via R+L's normal waste stream.

column168: Driver arrived to deliver a bulk load of VM&P to MFG in Dalton, GA. Customer informed driver that they would complete unload process, driver returned to the cab of his truck. Customer employee began sample taking process and checked that external valve was closed before opening internal valve to take sample. Upon opening internal valve, an estimated quantity of approximately 50 gallons was released unexpectedly out of the hose connection point and into the customers containment area. Probable cause is external valve failure. Tanker will be fully inspected to confirm.
column169: Tanker was taken back to Univar yard, cleaned and inspected. During inspection it was found that the internal valve was holding but the external valve was Ieaking. Once the external valve was removed you could see that there was a nut with a cotter pin that was missing. This was the cause of the release. On 9/28/2023 Cox Automotive came on site to Univar and fixed the valve. A new gasket and nut with cotter pin were put on the external valve where it had been missing. External valve will be tested again this evening to make sure repairs were done correctly.

column168: A Veolia driver initially picked up the drum in question on 9/5/2023 from the offeror and the trailer was used to pick up other materials on 9/12/23. The driver noticed that there was some liquid on the front of the trailer along with oily stains on the back of the trailer. Veolia personnel started to remove the drums from the trailer and identified the leaking drum which was located at the nose of the trailer. The leaking drum was a 55 gal metal drum with a pin hole leak that appeared to occur from potentially rubbing/impact against another drum during transportation which was a weak spot due to corrosion. The driver made multiple stops that day and he has stated that he did not notice any staining on the back-end of the trailer when he loaded addition drums at each stop. Also he did not notice any oily material near or around the front of the trailer during those stops. We are unsure of the duration of the spill but based on the quantity still left in the drum, roughly 5 gallons had leaked out. The drum was placed into a salvage drum and the spill clean up was completed by the Veolia in-house crew.  Most of the material was contained inside the trailer with minimal amounts outside of the trailer.  There was no evidence of a any spill on the ground itself.
column169: Based on the investigation, the drums are stored outdoors at the customer site which contributed to some corrosion and likely caused some weak spots on the drum. The driver stated that there was some surface rust on the drum but nothing that may have compromised the drum itself. Veolia will review this incident with all employees in regards to checking the drum to make sure that it is not compromised and if there is any surface corrosion to further evaluate and potentially place in salvage drum prior to transportation when there is doubt.

XPO Logistics terminal NMP experienced a customer location release of UN3098 Wheycide from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of product released to a 6' x 1' area of the trailer floor, and a 7' x 6' area of the concrete lot below due to a forklift puncture. Acid gator was deployed onto the impacted areas. The material remaining in the damaged drum was neutralized and solidified. The damaged empty drum was then containerized into a cubic yard box. All impacted absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon vented poly drums. The waste was then transported to the XPO terminal located in Memphis, TN, and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: The package was loaded at the site of the contractors truck.  A package handler noticed an odor and saw that the package was leaking and notified a manager.  The manager notified QA and the package was put in a tub, while Oil Dri was put on the spill.  The package was taken to the hazmat cage and transferred to an hazmat tub.  The oil dri was swept up and put into a hazmat bag. DescribePack: There was room for four bottles and the cardboard that was put on top was insufficient to keep the bottles from shifting.  One of the bottles broke in the middle and leaked out. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The package was put into a tub and Oil Dri was applied to the spill.  The Oil Dri was then swept up and put into a hazmat bag.

column168: On 2023-09-29 CN DGO was contacted via email by the Fond du Lac yardmaster, about a leaking tank car. During switching operations in the yard, the conductor smelled an odor as well noticed product leaking down the sides of tank car UTLX 201666 (L)UN3268 Class 3//(6.1)(8)//PG II. WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, TOXIC, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. / (POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE ISOPROPANOL ORGANIC PESTICIDE).  All CN departments were notified and the car was set out on NO61 for service and repair. I contacted a contractor to respond. Upon arrival and inspection of the car there was two of eight manway, securement bolts less then tool tight. After opening the manway there was found two gaskets one for the nozzle and another for the lid. The nozzle gasket was pinched and misaligned as the lid gasket was not of the correct size. Both gaskets were removed and the area cleaned. A new nozzle gasket was installed and the manway securement bolts were tightened tool tight. The car was cleaned of any residual product and released back to transportation to continue onto destination.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 9/30/23, at 2104, personnel in the CSXT Clifton Forge yard reported NATX400224, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, was suspected to leaking. The car was isolated and the shipper, Advansix, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2023-10-01-00001). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, as well as a CSXT Manager of Hazardous Materials, were dispatched to the scene and found product leaking through the pressure relief valve.  CSX and contractor personnel contained the release with application of an emergency capping kit until such time that the contents of the leaking car were transloaded into tank car NATX400291. Additionally, response personnel utilized a highway transport truck to unload approximately 4,000 liquid gallons of product that could not be safely loaded into the NATX 400291 due to volumetric outage constraints.  Because the leaking car was not equipped with a gauging device, response personnel were unable to determine the specific reason why the identified calf car could not accept the entire load; however, it is suspected that the NATX 400224 was originally overloaded prior to the pressure relief device failure.  Upon completion of the product transload, response personnel purged the leaking car to clean/empty status.  All issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Christian Beale 804-731-8124). While the car was suspected to be overloaded, the pressure relief device continued to leak for the duration of the unloading process- even at acceptable load volume and pressure.  Because of the this, the pressure relief device was identified as non-conforming and an AAR form QA 7.1 was filed.

On September 22, 2023, two (2) 5-gallon pails of UN3265 were crushed in transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from SET Environmental (SET) to remediate the impacted site.  The damaged jugs were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal. Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to the impacted area and utilized absorbent wipes to remove residual product from the remaining two (2) undamaged jugs. All UN3265-impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal UDV experienced a UN1789 Hydrochloric Acid 31% release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contactors for cleanup and containment. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-ounce of material released to the top of the tote in a 1’ x 1’ area due to a loose/damaged cap. The cap was replaced with a new one and the tote was wiped down with a sodium bicarb solution. The damaged cap, impacted rags, and PPE were then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 9/28/2023 a Veolia employee unloading drums from a truck into another trailer at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY 10 day intransit facility when the employee noticed that a 14 gallon fiber drum was stained and damp. The 14 gallon drum contained a 2.5 gallon glass bottle of Formic Acid With Not Less Than 5% But Less Than 10% Acid By Mass corrosive liquids. The outer container was opened and the inner container was inspected and was found to be broken and released its contents. No liquid was released from the outer packaging drum.   The 14 gallon drum containing the broken glass bottle was overpacked into an 30 gallon 1H2 drum and transportation to the ultimate disposal facility was continued. The drum did not leak any amount of the corrosive liquid solution out of the outer container.
column169: On 9/28/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. The results of the investigation is the employee who packaged the container did not know that the maximum allowable size of a glass container is limited to one gallon. We did follow up with that employee and reviewed 49 CFR 173.12(b)(2)(i). We will review this requirement with all other employees to make sure they are trained on the limit for glass containers being restricted to one gallon when packaged for transportation in accordance with 49 CFR 173.12.

column168: Location: FedEx Trade Networks Transport & Brokerage, Inc., 3700 Commerce Drive, East Point, GA 30344 08/29/23: Quality Importers Trading Company contacted our Miami branch office requesting a spot quote for two pallets from Miami, FL (MIA) to Erbil, Iraq (EBL) for non-hazardous materials cargo via air. 08/30/23: Quote# 20230830-457 was generated with non-hazardous rates. (See attached document) 09/05/23: Quality Importers approved the quote and sent our Miami office worker a Safety Data Sheet (SOS) for  butane (see attached SDS). Our worker questioned the customer as they had previously stated no  hazmat and that if there was, the quote would require updating. The customer responded that the  lighters were empty. After that conversation, Southeastern Freight Lines was contracted to pick up the shipment at origin address and move to our warehouse in East Point, GA. This air freight shipment was planned to be shipped on Turkish Airlines (TK) via passenger aircraft. 09/11/23: Southeastern Freight Lines picked up the two pallets from the shipper's facility. (See attached  BOL) 09/13/23: Upon arrival at our East Point, GA warehouse, our warehouse manager suspected that the shipment may contain hazardous materials based on a warehouse worker bringing attention to some odd markings on  the shrink-wrapped skids. The warehouse manager pulled the commercial invoices and an SDS for  butane off the shipment. On page 17 of the commercial invoice, butane is listed as being present in  12 cans at 8 ounces each. The odd markings are GHS labels reproduced on a paper sheet (see attached photographs). 09/14/23: Customer was contacted by our Miami office. Customer advises via email, "Yes, it contains butane cans. (Ten 12 pks of butane cans. Size 13.5 oz. per can) The lighters do not contain butane. They are empty. The commodities list for quote was not amended, sorry for that oversight as they were the last thing added to the order. " Our East Point warehouse engaged ProPack, a third party dangerous goods packer to identify the  hazmat and repack. They discovered a box that was loaded on the pallet in such a manner that the  pre-printed ground limited quantity mark was not viewable. Dry batteries under SP A123 were also discovered. I, Carla Andrews, Manager of Dangerous Goods/Safety was notified about an undeclared shipment. I  immediately put the shipment on hold until further notice. Upon my review of the commercial  invoice, I believed there were additional hazardous materials to potentially include lithium batteries. 09/15/23: I contacted the FAA as this shipment was scheduled to travel overseas by air. I spoke with Stan Satchell from the FAA about the shipment. Mr. Satchell informed me that FAA Safety Inspectors would arrive Monday, 09/17/23 to inspect the shipment. 09/18/23: At 1330 EDT, FAA Safety Inspectors Desmond Ruff and David Dixon arrived to inspect the shipment.  They also discovered a maintenance kit that contained compressed air and butane. They did
column169: The shipper needs to properly declare all hazardous materials at time of requesting a transportation quote and include all supporting documentation such as SOS and/or UN38.3 Test Summary Reports. The shipper's shipping department requires retraining per 49 CFR Subpart H commensurate with their duties. It is also suggested that the shipper created Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) for each type of hazardous material they ship.

On 09/19/2023, at 1042 hrs. Personnel in the CSXT Ottawa Yard discovered MTZX330221, a residue tank car of Propane, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and NGL Supply Wholesale LLC, NRC, Illinois EMA, Ottawa Fire Department were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2023091900178. (RMS), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the secondary closure not applied and laying on the pressure plate and the A-end liquid line valve open 1/8th of a turn). The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Jamee Spears 501-680-2267). Contractor personnel closed the valve, cleaned the threads of the secondary plug, applied new thread tape and tool tightened it in place. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident (did not) require a special switching move.  No 7.1 is required.  Cause Code: 312 NARRI: 5
